{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621490"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16719"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16719"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.1,0.15,0.05,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66538"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9410"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51991"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7166"},{"type":"tags","id":"7178"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22267"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22268"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66538"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is reviewing the anatomy of the autonomic nervous system. They are particularly interested in understanding the location of preganglionic sympathetic neurons.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following spinal cord levels contains the cell bodies of preganglionic sympathetic neurons in the lateral horn of grey matter?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T2 to L4","T1 to L5","T1 to L4","S2 to S4","T1 to L2"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe preganglionic sympathetic neurons are located in the lateral horn of the spinal cord grey matter between \u003Cstrong\u003ET1 to L2\u003C/strong\u003E segments. This is known as the thoracolumbar outflow of the sympathetic nervous system. These neurons synapse with postganglionic neurons in the sympathetic chain ganglia or collateral ganglia, which then innervate target organs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET2 to L4\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it extends too far caudally and misses the first thoracic segment. No sympathetic preganglionic neurons exist below L2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET1 to L5\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as sympathetic preganglionic neurons do not extend beyond L2. The segments from L3 to L5 contain only somatic motor and sensory neurons in their grey matter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET1 to L4\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect for the same reason - sympathetic preganglionic neurons do not extend this far caudally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ES2 to S4\u003C/strong\u003E represents the levels where parasympathetic preganglionic neurons are found (along with S1), not sympathetic neurons. This forms part of the craniosacral outflow of the parasympathetic nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this anatomical arrangement is crucial as it explains why conditions affecting the spinal cord at different levels can have varying effects on autonomic function. For example, spinal cord injuries above T1 can result in loss of sympathetic function below the level of injury, while those below L2 spare sympathetic function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Preganglionic sympathetic neurons originate from the lateral horn of the spinal cord between T1 and L2 segments.","This anatomical arrangement is crucial for understanding the distribution of sympathetic innervation throughout the body.","The thoracolumbar outflow of the sympathetic nervous system contrasts with the craniosacral parasympathetic outflow."],"references":["Deuchars SA, Lall VK. Sympathetic preganglionic neurons: properties and inputs. Compr Physiol. 2015 Apr;5(2):829-69. doi: 10.1002/cphy.c140020. PMID: 25880515.","Gibbins I. Functional organization of autonomic neural pathways. Organogenesis. 2013 Jul-Sep;9(3):169-75. doi: 10.4161/org.25126. Epub 2013 Jun 6. PMID: 23872517; PMCID: PMC3896588.","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51991"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16719"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51991"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T19:00:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T19:01:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9410"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66538"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"h